'''Hocus pocus''' is a generic term that may be derived from an ancient language and is currently used by stage [[Magician (illusion)|magicians]], usually the [[magic word]]s spoken when bringing about some sort of change. It was once a common term for a magician, [[Juggling|juggler]], or other similar [[entertainers]].
== History == The earliest known [[English language|English-language]] work on magic, or what was then known as ''[[legerdemain]]'' (sleight of hand), was published anonymously in 1635 under the title ''Hocus Pocus Junior: The Anatomie of Legerdemain''.<ref>[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/34375/34375-h/34375-h.htm "Hocus Pocus Junior: The Anatomie of Legerdemain"]</ref> Further research suggests that "Hocus Pocus" was the stage name of a well known magician of the era. This may be William Vincent, who is recorded as having been granted a license to perform magic in [[England]] in 1619.<ref>[http://www.hocuspocusjr.com/hocvspocvsjr.htm The Web Site About the First Illustrated Book in the English Language Devoted Entirely to the Subject of Magic]</ref> Whether he was the author of the book is unknown.
== Conjectured origins == {{Refimprove |section| date = June 2016 | talk = y }} The origins of the term remain obscure. The most popular conjecture is that it is a garbled Latin religious phrase or some form of [[dog Latin|‘dog’ Latin]]. Some have associated it with similar-sounding fictional, mythical, or legendary names. Others dismiss it as merely a combination of [[nonsense word]]s.
In some [[Slavic language]]s, "pokus" means an "attempt" or an "experiment", as for example in [[Czech language|Czech]] or [[Slovak language]]. The word is derived from the [[Protoslavic]] word "kusiti", which is itself derived from [[Gothic language|Gothic]] "kausajn" meaning "to try", "to attempt".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Králik|first1=Ľubor|title=Stručný etymologický slovník slovenčiny|date=2015|publisher=Veda}}</ref> This may indicate that the wording belongs to the [[alchemy]] kitchen and court of [[Rudolf II, Holy Roman Emperor]] (1552 – 1612). Also, ''hocus'' may mean "to cheat" in Latin or a distorted form of the word ''hoc'', "this". Combination of the two words may give a sense, especially both meanings together "this attempt/experiment" and "cheated attempt/experiment".{{cn|date=December 2016}}
=== Dog Latin === According to the [[Oxford English Dictionary]] the term originates from ''hax pax max Deus adimax'', a [[pseudo-Latin]] phrase used as a [[magical formula]] by [[Conjuror|conjurors]].<ref>Compact Oxford English Dictionary. [http://www.askoxford.com/concise_oed/hocuspocus] http://www.askoxford.com/concise_oed/hocuspocus</ref>
Some believe it originates from a corruption or [[parody]] of the [[Catholic liturgy]] of the [[Eucharist (Catholic Church)|Eucharist]], which contains the phrase “''[[Words of Institution|Hoc est enim corpus meum]]''”, meaning ''This is my body''.<ref>''Online Etymology Dictionary'' [http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=hocus-pocus] http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=hocus-pocus</ref> This explanation goes back to speculations by the [[Church of England|Anglican]] [[prelate]] [[John Tillotson]], who wrote in 1694:{{Quote|In all probability those common juggling words of ''hocus pocus'' are nothing else but a corruption of ''hoc est corpus'', by way of ridiculous imitation of the priests of the [[Catholic Church|Church of Rome]] in their trick of [[Transubstantiation]].<ref>[http://www.randomhouse.com/wotd/index.pperl?date=19991007 Random House Words@Random: The Mavens' Word of the Day]; see [[Talk:Hocus Pocus (magic)]] for full quotation</ref>}}
This claim is substantiated by the fact that in the [[Netherlands]], the words ''Hocus pocus'' are usually accompanied by the additional words ''pilatus pas'', and this is said to be based on a post-[[Protestant Reformation|Reformation]] parody of the traditional Catholic rite of [[transubstantiation]] during [[Mass (Catholic Church)|Mass]], being a Dutch corruption of the [[Latin]] words "''Hoc est corpus meum''" and the [[credo]], which reads in part, "''sub [[Pontius Pilate|Pontio Pilato]] [[Passion (Christianity)|passus]] et [[Burial of Jesus|sepultus est]]''", meaning ''under Pontius Pilate he suffered and was buried''.<ref>In de Kou, ''[[Godfried Bomans]] en Michel van der Plas over hun roomse jeugd en hoe het hun verging'', Amsterdam, 1969</ref> In a similar way the phrase is in [[Scandinavia]] usually accompanied by ''filiokus'', a corruption of the term [[filioque]],{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}} from the [[Latin Church|Latin]] version of the [[Nicene Creed]], meaning “''and from the Son''”. The variant spelling ''filipokus'' is common in [[Russia]], a predominantly [[Eastern Orthodox]] nation, as well as certain other post-[[Soviet Union|Soviet]] states.{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}} Additionally, the word for "stage trick" in [[Russian language|Russian]], ''fokus'', is derived from ''hocus pocus''.{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}}
=== Magician’s name === Others believe that it is an appeal to the folkloric [[Norse mythology|Norse]] magician Ochus Bochus:{{Quote|text=Hocus Pocus: Words of pseudomagical import. According to [[Sharon Turner]] in ''The History of the Anglo-Saxons'' (4 vols., 1799-1805), they were believed to be derived from ''Ochus Bochus'', a magician and [[demon]] of the north.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}}}
=== Nonsense word === As an alternative to other theories, it may simply be [[pseudo-Latin]] with no meaning, made up to impress people:{{Quote|text=I will speak of one man... that went about in King James his time ... who called himself, “''The Kings Majesties most excellent Hocus Pocus''”, and so was he called, because that at the playing of every Trick, he used to say, “''Hocus pocus, tontus talontus, vade celeriter jubeo''”, a dark composure of words, to blinde the eyes of the beholders, to make his Trick pass the more currently without discovery, because when the eye and the ear of the beholder are both earnestly busied, the Trick is not so easily discovered, nor the Imposture discerned.|author=[[Thomas Ady]] |source= ''A Candle in the Dark'', 1656<ref>[http://www.phrases.org.uk/meanings/hocus-pocus.html The Phrase Finder.]</ref>}}
